{"parse":{"title":"List of enlightened despots","pageid":49455496,"revid":858810556,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-style ambox-essay-like\" role=\"presentation\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"mbox-image\"><div style=\"width:52px\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edit-clear.svg.png\" width=\"40\" height=\"40\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/60px-Edit-clear.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/80px-Edit-clear.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"48\" data-file-height=\"48\" /></div></td><td class=\"mbox-text\"><div class=\"mbox-text-span\">This article <b>is written like a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:NOTESSAY\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wikipedia:NOTESSAY\">personal reflection or opinion essay</a></b> that states a Wikipedia editor's personal feelings about a topic.<span class=\"hide-when-compact\"> Please <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_enlightened_despots&amp;action=edit\">help improve it</a> by rewriting it in an <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Encyclopedic_style\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wikipedia:Encyclopedic style\">encyclopedic style</a>.</span>  <small><i>(November 2016)</i></small><small class=\"hide-when-compact\"><i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal\" title=\"Help:Maintenance template removal\">Learn how and when to remove this template message</a>)</i></small></div></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>An <b>Enlightened despot</b> (also called <b>benevolent despot</b>) is an <a href=\"/wiki/Authoritarian\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Authoritarian\">authoritarian</a> or non-<a href=\"/wiki/Democracy\" title=\"Democracy\">democratic</a> leader who exercises his political power for the benefit of the people, rather than exclusively for themselves or for an elite or small portion of the people.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Historically they were <a href=\"/wiki/Monarch\" title=\"Monarch\">monarchs</a> making use of enlightened ideas and principles in order to enhance the central government's power (thereby their own power).<sup id=\"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPerryChaseJacob2015442_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPerryChaseJacob2015442-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Most were directly linked to <a href=\"/wiki/The_Enlightenment\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"The Enlightenment\">the Enlightenment</a> period in the <a href=\"/wiki/18th_century\" title=\"18th century\">18th</a> and early <a href=\"/wiki/19th_century\" title=\"19th century\">19th centuries</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Characteristics\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Characteristics</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Famous_enlightened_despots\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Famous enlightened despots</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Enlightened_despots_in_recent_history\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Enlightened despots in recent history</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Characteristics\">Characteristics</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=List_of_enlightened_despots&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Characteristics\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">Main article: <a href=\"/wiki/Enlightened_absolutism\" title=\"Enlightened absolutism\">Enlightened absolutism</a></div>\n<p>Enlightened despots were monarchs who distinguished themselves from <a href=\"/wiki/Despotism\" title=\"Despotism\">despots</a> (in the ordinary sense) by the way they governed; they claimed to rule for the well-being of their subjects. For example, an enlightened despot may focus government priorities on matters of public importance such as <a href=\"/wiki/Healthcare\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Healthcare\">healthcare</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Education\" title=\"Education\">education</a>, nonviolent population control, or physical infrastructure. He or she may be committed to <a href=\"/wiki/Peace\" title=\"Peace\">peaceful</a> relations and may even allow for some democratic decision-making to exist, such as public <a href=\"/wiki/Referendum\" title=\"Referendum\">referendums,</a> but did not propose reforms that would undermine their sovereignty or disrupt social order. As <a href=\"/wiki/John_Stuart_Mill\" title=\"John Stuart Mill\">John Stuart Mill</a> articulated: \"Despotism is a legitimate mode of government in dealing with barbarians, provided the end be their improvement.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMill198913_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMill198913-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Although their reigns were based upon Enlightenment principles, their beliefs about royal power were similar to those of regular despots. Enlightened despots believed that they were destined to be ruler the moment they were born.\n</p><p>Enlightened rulers may have played a part in the abolition of serfdom in Europe.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Joseph_II,_Holy_Roman_Emperor\" title=\"Joseph II, Holy Roman Emperor\">Emperor Joseph II</a> once said: \"Everything for the people, nothing by the people\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Most dictatorial regimes portray themselves as enlightened and often tend to regard democratic regimes as messy, inefficient, and corrupt. Additionally, many dictators may attempt to openly spread misinformation about their enlightenment, real or assumed, in an attempt to create a <a href=\"/wiki/Personality_cult\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Personality cult\">personality cult</a>.\n</p><p>In the Spanish language the word <i><a href=\"/wiki/Dictablanda\" title=\"Dictablanda\">dictablanda</a></i> is sometimes used for a dictatorship that preserves some of the liberties and mechanisms of democracy.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Famous_enlightened_despots\">Famous enlightened despots</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=List_of_enlightened_despots&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Famous enlightened despots\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The most famous enlightened despots in history were:\n</p>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Catherine_the_Great\" title=\"Catherine the Great\">Catherine the Great of Russia</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Charles_III_of_Spain\" title=\"Charles III of Spain\">Carlos III of Spain</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-H.M._Scott,_1990,_p._1_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-H.M._Scott,_1990,_p._1-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Frederick_the_Great\" title=\"Frederick the Great\">Frederick the Great of Prussia</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Frederick_VI_of_Denmark\" title=\"Frederick VI of Denmark\">Frederick VI of Denmark</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-H._Arnold_Barton_1986_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-H._Arnold_Barton_1986-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Gustav_III_of_Sweden\" title=\"Gustav III of Sweden\">Gustav III of Sweden</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-H._Arnold_Barton_1986_9-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-H._Arnold_Barton_1986-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Joseph_II,_Holy_Roman_Emperor\" title=\"Joseph II, Holy Roman Emperor\">Joseph II, Holy Roman Emperor of Austria</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-H.M._Scott,_1990,_p._1_7-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-H.M._Scott,_1990,_p._1-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Joseph_I_of_Portugal\" title=\"Joseph I of Portugal\">Joseph I of Portugal</a> (through his minister the Marquis of Pombal)</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Maria_Theresa\" title=\"Maria Theresa\">Maria Theresa</a> of Austria</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Leopold_II,_Holy_Roman_Emperor\" title=\"Leopold II, Holy Roman Emperor\">Leopold I, Grand Duke of Tuscany</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-H.M._Scott,_1990,_p._1_7-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-H.M._Scott,_1990,_p._1-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Louis_XVI_of_France\" title=\"Louis XVI of France\">Louis XVI of France</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-H.M._Scott,_1990,_p._1_7-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-H.M._Scott,_1990,_p._1-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Maria_Carolina_of_Austria\" title=\"Maria Carolina of Austria\">Maria Carolina of Austria</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_Neapolitan_consorts\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"List of Neapolitan consorts\">Queen of Naples</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Christian_VII_of_Denmark\" title=\"Christian VII of Denmark\">Christian VII of Denmark</a> (through his minister <a href=\"/wiki/Johann_Friedrich_Struensee\" title=\"Johann Friedrich Struensee\">Johann Friedrich Struensee</a>)</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Napoleon_Bonaparte\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Napoleon Bonaparte\">Napoleon Bonaparte</a></li></ul>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r856303569\">@media all and (max-width:720px){.mw-parser-output .tmulti>.thumbinner{width:100%!important;max-width:none!important}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .tsingle{float:none!important;max-width:none!important;width:100%!important;text-align:center}}</style><div class=\"thumb tmulti tnone center\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:995px;max-width:995px\"><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"float:left;margin:1px;width:172px;max-width:172px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Charles_III_of_Spain_high_resolution.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Charles_III_of_Spain_high_resolution.jpg/170px-Charles_III_of_Spain_high_resolution.jpg\" width=\"170\" height=\"238\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Charles_III_of_Spain_high_resolution.jpg/255px-Charles_III_of_Spain_high_resolution.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Charles_III_of_Spain_high_resolution.jpg/340px-Charles_III_of_Spain_high_resolution.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2178\" data-file-height=\"3051\" /></a></div></div><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"float:left;margin:1px;width:167px;max-width:167px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Catherinethegreatroslin.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/50/Catherinethegreatroslin.jpg/165px-Catherinethegreatroslin.jpg\" width=\"165\" height=\"239\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/50/Catherinethegreatroslin.jpg/248px-Catherinethegreatroslin.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/50/Catherinethegreatroslin.jpg/330px-Catherinethegreatroslin.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"866\" data-file-height=\"1255\" /></a></div></div><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"float:left;margin:1px;width:155px;max-width:155px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Gustav_III_of_Sweden_1.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Gustav_III_of_Sweden_1.jpg/153px-Gustav_III_of_Sweden_1.jpg\" width=\"153\" height=\"238\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Gustav_III_of_Sweden_1.jpg/230px-Gustav_III_of_Sweden_1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Gustav_III_of_Sweden_1.jpg/306px-Gustav_III_of_Sweden_1.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"642\" data-file-height=\"1000\" /></a></div></div><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"float:left;margin:1px;width:144px;max-width:144px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:D._Jos%C3%A9_I_de_Portugal.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/D._Jos%C3%A9_I_de_Portugal.jpg/142px-D._Jos%C3%A9_I_de_Portugal.jpg\" width=\"142\" height=\"237\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/D._Jos%C3%A9_I_de_Portugal.jpg/213px-D._Jos%C3%A9_I_de_Portugal.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/D._Jos%C3%A9_I_de_Portugal.jpg/284px-D._Jos%C3%A9_I_de_Portugal.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"344\" data-file-height=\"575\" /></a></div></div><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"float:left;margin:1px;width:172px;max-width:172px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Anton_von_Maron_006.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Anton_von_Maron_006.png/170px-Anton_von_Maron_006.png\" width=\"170\" height=\"240\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Anton_von_Maron_006.png/255px-Anton_von_Maron_006.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Anton_von_Maron_006.png/340px-Anton_von_Maron_006.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1138\" data-file-height=\"1609\" /></a></div></div><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"float:left;margin:1px;width:173px;max-width:173px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Antoine-Fran%C3%A7ois_Callet_-_Louis_XVI,_roi_de_France_et_de_Navarre_(1754-1793),_rev%C3%AAtu_du_grand_costume_royal_en_1779_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Antoine-Fran%C3%A7ois_Callet_-_Louis_XVI%2C_roi_de_France_et_de_Navarre_%281754-1793%29%2C_rev%C3%AAtu_du_grand_costume_royal_en_1779_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/171px-Antoine-Fran%C3%A7ois_Callet_-_Louis_XVI%2C_roi_de_France_et_de_Navarre_%281754-1793%29%2C_rev%C3%AAtu_du_grand_costume_royal_en_1779_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg\" width=\"171\" height=\"241\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Antoine-Fran%C3%A7ois_Callet_-_Louis_XVI%2C_roi_de_France_et_de_Navarre_%281754-1793%29%2C_rev%C3%AAtu_du_grand_costume_royal_en_1779_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/257px-Antoine-Fran%C3%A7ois_Callet_-_Louis_XVI%2C_roi_de_France_et_de_Navarre_%281754-1793%29%2C_rev%C3%AAtu_du_grand_costume_royal_en_1779_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Antoine-Fran%C3%A7ois_Callet_-_Louis_XVI%2C_roi_de_France_et_de_Navarre_%281754-1793%29%2C_rev%C3%AAtu_du_grand_costume_royal_en_1779_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/342px-Antoine-Fran%C3%A7ois_Callet_-_Louis_XVI%2C_roi_de_France_et_de_Navarre_%281754-1793%29%2C_rev%C3%AAtu_du_grand_costume_royal_en_1779_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"3592\" data-file-height=\"5062\" /></a></div></div><div style=\"clear:left\"></div><div class=\"thumbcaption\" style=\"clear:left;text-align:left;background-color:transparent\">Examples of Enlightened Absolutism monarchs: <a href=\"/wiki/Charles_III_of_Spain\" title=\"Charles III of Spain\">Charles III of Spain</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Catherine_the_Great\" title=\"Catherine the Great\">Catherine II of Russia</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Gustav_III_of_Sweden\" title=\"Gustav III of Sweden\">Gustav III of Sweden</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Joseph_I_of_Portugal\" title=\"Joseph I of Portugal\">Joseph I of Portugal</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Joseph_II_of_Austria\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Joseph II of Austria\">Joseph II of Austria</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Louis_XVI_of_France\" title=\"Louis XVI of France\">Louis XVI of France</a></div></div></div>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Enlightened_despots_in_recent_history\">Enlightened despots in recent history</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=List_of_enlightened_despots&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Enlightened despots in recent history\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Like many <a href=\"/wiki/Political\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Political\">political</a> classifications, the title of enlightened despot suffers from its inherent subjectivity. In recent history strong, ruthless dictators such as <a href=\"/wiki/Lee_Kuan_Yew\" title=\"Lee Kuan Yew\">Lee Kuan Yew</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Josip_Broz_Tito\" title=\"Josip Broz Tito\">Josip Broz Tito</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Ant%C3%B3nio_Salazar\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ant\u00f3nio Salazar\">Ant\u00f3nio Salazar</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Isaias_Afwerki\" title=\"Isaias Afwerki\">Isaias Afwerki</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Park_Chung-hee\" title=\"Park Chung-hee\">Park Chung-hee</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Chiang_Kai-shek\" title=\"Chiang Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Pervez_Musharraf\" title=\"Pervez Musharraf\">Pervez Musharraf</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Thomas_Sankara\" title=\"Thomas Sankara\">Thomas Sankara</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Muammar_Gaddafi\" title=\"Muammar Gaddafi\">Muammar Gaddafi</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Saddam_Hussein\" title=\"Saddam Hussein\">Saddam Hussein</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Bashar_al-Assad\" title=\"Bashar al-Assad\">Bashar al-Assad</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Vladimir_Putin\" title=\"Vladimir Putin\">Vladimir Putin</a> can be characterized as enlightened despots. In all of these cases the point of view as to just how \"enlightened\" or \"dictatorial\" they are is largely subjective.\n</p><p>Generally, dictators who serve in office for a very long period are more likely to be regarded as enlightened because they will often be forced to pay some attention to the public interest in order to remain in power and, more importantly, to be regarded as <a href=\"/wiki/Legitimacy_(political)\" title=\"Legitimacy (political)\">legitimate</a>. Dictators who hold office for a brief period of time or are simply members of a rotating dictatorial elite (such as those heading some <a href=\"/wiki/Totalitarianism\" title=\"Totalitarianism\">juntas</a>) may have less <a href=\"/wiki/Charismatic_authority\" title=\"Charismatic authority\">charismatic authority</a> and prove to be forgettable and are therefore often easier to demonize. In the cases of dictators such as Saddam Hussein and Muammar Gaddafi their enlightened qualities became apparent only in the wake of the breakdown of state institutions and persecution of religious and ethnic minorities that followed their removal from power.<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=List_of_enlightened_despots&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Authoritarianism\" title=\"Authoritarianism\">Authoritarianism</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Noblesse_oblige\" title=\"Noblesse oblige\">Noblesse oblige</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=List_of_enlightened_despots&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.britannica.com/topic/enlightened-despotism\">http://www.britannica.com/topic/enlightened-despotism</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-FOOTNOTEPerryChaseJacob2015442-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPerryChaseJacob2015442_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"#CITEREFPerryChaseJacob2015\">Perry, Chase &amp; Jacob 2015</a>, p.&#160;442.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-FOOTNOTEMill198913-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMill198913_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"#CITEREFMill1989\">Mill 1989</a>, p.&#160;13.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.1902encyclopedia.com/S/SLA/slavery-12.html\">\"Disappearance of Serfdom. France. England. Italy. Germany. Spain\"</a>. <i>www.1902encyclopedia.com</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2015-12-07</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=www.1902encyclopedia.com